[Sliding Window Algorithm Technique][1] is your friend! You can do it with **O(n)**.

```java
public static long findThreeConsecutiveSum(Iterator&lt;Integer&gt; it) {
    long maxSum = Long.MIN_VALUE;
    long curSum = 0;
    Deque&lt;Integer&gt; deque = new ArrayDeque&lt;&gt;(4);

    while (it.hasNext()) {
        int val = it.next();

        curSum += val;
        deque.addLast(val);

        if (deque.size() == 4) {
            curSum -= deque.removeFirst();
        }

        maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, curSum);
    }


    return maxSum;
}
```

or in case you can&#39;t use `Deque`:

```java
public static long findThreeConsecutiveSum(Iterator&lt;Integer&gt; it) {
    long maxSum = Long.MIN_VALUE;
    int[] arr = new int[3];
    int i = 0;

    while (it.hasNext()) {
        int val = it.next();

        if (i == arr.length) {
            arr[0] = arr[1];
            arr[1] = arr[2];
            arr[2] = val;
        } else
            arr[i++] = val;

        maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, arr[0] + arr[1] + arr[2]);
    }


    return maxSum;
}
```

**Demo**

```java
List&lt;Integer&gt; values = List.of(7, 2, 9, 8, 7, 6, 7, 5, 9);
long maxSum = findThreeConsecutiveSum(values.iterator());
System.out.println(maxSum); // 24
```

  [1]: https://Sliding%20Window%20Algorithm%20Technique

